AGI - Independence, yes, but when? Today the Greenlanders will vote for the legislative elections, a fundamental moment to establish when breaking ties with Denmark, the current protection power, without falling into the clutches of Donald Trump. The insistence, sometimes threatening, of the American president in wanting to take possession of Greenland has given impetus to the independent aspirations of the 57,000 inhabitants of the territory, many of which claim not to be either Danes or Americans, but Greenland.
&nbsp;
"Donald Trump has in a way raised the question of independence," explains Maria Ackren of the University of Greenland. "This is not a novelty for the Greenland, but now provides Greenland decision-makers and politicians a stimulus to achieve perhaps goals that were not possible until now." The issue has taken an important place in the election campaign, including education, social affairs, fisheries (which accounts for 90% of island exports) and tourism.
&nbsp;
Almost all political parties would like the vast frozen territory, 50 times larger than Denmark but 100 times less populated, to fly alone. The numerous cranes that rise above Nuuk, the capital, testify to a rapid modernization that made vulnerable part of the population, largely Inuit, dedicated to hunting and fishing. Visible to the naked eye, social misery is also found in statistics: a rate of suicide among the highest in the world, a number of abortions greater than that of births, a life expectancy less than 70 years for men. Although the desire for independence is widely shared, the political parties competing for the 31 seats of Parliament disagree on the times.
&nbsp;
Among the most impatient, the nationalist party Naleraq (opposition), very visible during the campaign, asks that the independence process begin as soon as possible. In the previous elections of 2021 he obtained 12% of the votes. "The interest we are finding, not only in the United States but also in the rest of the world, is in our favor," says Juno Berthelsen, one of the top candidates "We can risk an estimate: this will happen in one or two electoral cycles - of four years each - but will depend on how the negotiations between Greenland and Denmark will go".
&nbsp;
Colonized by Danes more than three centuries ago, the Arctic island gained autonomy in 1979, but the functions of sovereignty (foreign affairs, defence) still compete in Copenhagen. Thanks to a 2009 law, the Greenlanders can autonomously start the independence process, which provides for the negotiation of an agreement with Denmark, which must then be approved by a referendum in Greenland and by a vote in the Danish Parliament. The two members of the outgoing coalition, Inuit Ataqatigiit (IA, the left Green Party of Prime Minister Mute Egede) and Siumut (the Social Democratic Party), are less in a hurry, but there may be internal divisions.
&nbsp;
They demand that the territory first achieve a certain economic sustainability, since the annual aid of approximately 530 million euros provided by Copenhagen represents a fifth of its GDP. "The debates on independence are still on the table. This is the final goal for many of us in Greenland, but it will take 10, 20 years or more", says Aaja Chemnitz, member of the IA and one of the two representatives of Greenland in the Danish Parliament "It is important to talk about the economic development of Greenland and how to achieve it in a much more sustainable way". The head of Siumut, Erik Jensen, Minister of Finance, is annoyed by the fact that the question of independence has eclipsed, at least in foreign and Danish media, those linked to the daily life of people.
&nbsp;
"Even independence is an important aspect of our program, but here in Greenland everyone speaks of health, schools and nurseries," he says. In the windy streets of Nuuk, the inhabitants swing between the desire for escape and economic realism: the exploitation of the island's mineral resources, often presented as a new financial launch pad, is still in embryonic phase. &nbsp;
<h2> Some things to know about Greenland
The Danish autonomous territory of Greenland, whose inhabitants tomorrow are called to vote for the legislative elections, has been catapulted in the spotlight for US ambitions for its natural resources and its strategic geographical position. Here are five things to know about Greenland
The island was originally nicknamed "Green Land" by Erik the Red, a Viking explorer landing at the southern end of the island in the 10th century. An inappropriate name, since about 80% of its surface of over two million square kilometers is covered with ice. Colonized by Denmark 300 years ago, it was integrated into the Kingdom of Denmark in 1953. In 1979, Copenhagen granted Greenland the extended autonomy with a 2009 law, although Copenhagen still decides on foreign policy and military issues. The economy, based mainly on the fisheries industry, depends strongly on Copenhagen's subsidies for more than 550 million euros, equivalent to one-fifth of the island's GDP. Contrary to Denmark, Greenland is not a member of the European Union from which it retired in 1985. Over 90 percent of its 57,000 inhabitants, about 19,000 of which live in the capital Nuuk, are Inuit.<br> <br> The ambitions of the United States
President Donald Trump has repeatedly stated since December that the United States plans to take possession of Greenland, raising tones in a speech at the Congress on March 4. "We really need it for international security. And I think we'll get it," he said. The United States' interest in the territory is not a novelty: in the Monroe Doctrine of 1823, the United States claimed that Greenland was part of its "sphere of interests". Nearly a century later, in 1917, Washington acquired the Virgin Islands from Denmark and recognized Denmark's sovereignty over Greenland. During World War II, when Denmark was occupied by Germany, Greenland passed under the protection of the United States and was returned to Denmark at the end of the war. The United States maintained several large military bases and one of them, Pituffik, in the northwest of the island, is still in use. The United States also has a consulate in Nuuk.&nbsp;
Palate minerals >
<br Greenland soil is rich in unused mineral and oil reserves, but on a global scale the quantities are modest. And now there are only two mines in use. The rare lands of Greenland, whose demand should increase in the future, are estimated in 36,1 billion tons by the Geological Survey of Denmark and Greenland (GEUS), but its reserves economically and technically recoverable, amount to only about 1.5 million tons. The public opposition to the extraction of uranium in southern Greenland has also led to a law prohibiting any extraction of radioactive materials. It is also believed that the island is located on an abundance of oil and gas, but it suspended exploration for fears related to environmental protection and aims instead to develop hydroelectric energy. Glacier melting is also releasing a mineral-rich rock flour that can be used as a fertilizer in impoverished or arid soils in Africa and South America.<br> <br> First line of global warming >
The enormous territory is experiencing firsthand the effects of global warming, with the Arctic being heated four times faster than the rest of the planet. If the ice mass, the second largest in the world after Antarctica, would dissolve completely, it could cause a rise in the sea level of more than seven meters.<br> <br> <br> Northern rocks &nbsp;>
Greenland does not have a road or rail network, so for transport we rely on helicopters, planes and boats. The increase in temperatures and the dissolution of the ices are in the meantime opening new and shorter navigation routes, strengthening the strategic position of the territory. It counts on tourism growth to boost its economy: in November the airport of Nuuk was open to long-range flights, making international access to the territory easier.&nbsp;
